<Sect3 Id="DFSAGR.FTMGT.div.12">
<Title>Learning Fileset Locations from Fileset Names or ID Numbers</Title>
<IndexTerm Id="DFSAGR.FTMGT.indx.30">
<Primary>filesets</Primary>
<Secondary>locations</Secondary>
</IndexTerm>
<IndexTerm Id="DFSAGR.FTMGT.indx.31">
<Primary><Command>fts</Command> command suite</Primary>
<Secondary><Command>lsfldb</Command>, alternative use</Secondary>
</IndexTerm>
<Para>To learn the location of a fileset from its name or ID number, enter the
<Command>fts lsfldb</Command> command with the <Option>fileset</Option> option:
</Para>
<InformalExample>
<Para><ProgramListing><UserInput>$ <Command>fts lsfldb -fileset </Command>{<Symbol Role="Variable">name</Symbol> | <Symbol Role="Variable">ID</Symbol>}
</UserInput></ProgramListing></Para>
</InformalExample>
<Para>The <Command>fts lsfldb</Command> command concludes its output with a list of the File
Server machines that house existing versions of the fileset. (See Section
7.3.1 for a thorough description of the command's output.)
</Para>
<Para>The following example displays the name of the File Server machine that houses
the fileset named <Replaceable>user.terry</Replaceable>:
<?sml-break><?sml-need 20></Para>
<InformalExample>
<Para><ProgramListing><UserInput>$ <Literal>fts lsfldb user.terry</Literal>
</UserInput></ProgramListing></Para>
</InformalExample>
